did.abstract: In 1960, due to the development of co-educational living centers, the then-existing Men's and Women's Residence Halls Associations were combined into one co-educational organization, the Residence Halls Association. Records in this collection include but are not limited to correspondence, minutes, memos, publications, election and committee files, and reports from just before its establishment, 1956, through 2007. The bulk of the collection dates between 1980 and 1996.

accessrestrict.head: Access Restrictions
accessrestrict.p: This collection is open for research.

bioghist.head: Historical Note
bioghist.p: The formation of the Residence Halls Association at Indiana University was a historic event. In 1960, due to the development of co-educational living centers, the then-existing Men's and Women's Residence Halls Associations were combined into one co-educational organization. This was a gender-related breakthrough that was symbolic of the changes in student life during the 60's era. This unique organization was called the Inter Residence Halls Association, or IRHA. In 1969, after a major constitutional revision, the decision was made to change the name to the Residence Halls Association, or RHA, which was enacted officially in 1976.

The RHA is made up of all the undergraduate students who live in the Indiana University campus residence halls and pay the minimal activities fee to become members. The purpose of this organization is three-fold: 1) to give students a voice in the policies and programs of their residence halls; 2) to promote a diverse, comfortable living environment; and, 3) to provide students with leadership opportunities.

The main governing body of the RHA is the President's Council. This council is made up of each center's president, the RHA president, vice president, and treasurer and three other executive officers. The purpose of the President's Council is to organize and direct policy for the center governments. They meet biweekly, usually in one of the residence centers, to discuss general affairs of the residence hall; present and vote on bills and resolutions for the residence halls; and discuss any other information or action pertinent to the governing bodies and activities of the RHA. Aside from the President's Council, each center has its own president, and each unit within the center has a governor. All the governors of the center make up a Board of Governors, which communicates the needs of the individual units to the center president, who then communicates them to the President's Council. Many specific problems and activities of the residence halls are dealt with by several committees within the RHA. Some of these committees include: the Judicial Board, the Damage Committee, and the Community Council.

To effectively fulfill its commitment to be a voice of the students of the residence halls, RHA relies on several liaisons to communicate with university administrators. The main line of communication for the RHA is through the Vice President of Internal Affairs. The Vice President of External Affairs acts as the RHA ambassador to other campus organizations such as IUSA. The Halls of Residence Committee is the liaison to the Vice President of the University. This group is made up of faculty and student leaders, and its purpose is to evaluate the current and future needs of the residence halls and forward these to the Vice President.

Specific services provided through the RHA include various planned programs and activities such as dances, sports tournaments, and general entertainment. Many centers have stores that offer convenience and personal hygiene goods and snack bar items. The halls even provide orientation courses in the dorms that teach freshman basic college survival skills.

The RHA of today still functions much like it did at its inception. To meet the needs of students in the 21st century many new issues have been addressed proving RHA's continued relevancy. Many new issues have been addressed, including up-to-date and readily available technologies and services including computer labs in each center and advanced Internet connection in most dorm rooms.

arrangement.head: Arrangement
arrangement.p: Organized into seven series: Correspondence, Administrative files, Committee files, Elections, President's Council, Subject files, and Vice President Files.

scopecontent.head: Scope and Content Note
scopecontent.p: This collection contains files from the Residence Halls Association. The earliest records date from just before the establishment of the RHA and run through 2007. The collection is organized into seven series: Correspondence, Administrative files, Committee files, Elections, President's Council, Subject files, and Vice President files.

The Correspondence series spans the years 1966-2001 and is arranged alphabetically. This series includes correspondence of members of the association with other members, faculty advisors, and various outside affiliates. Also included are letters of complaint from alumni and students concerning the actions of the RHA.

The Administrative files series spans the years from 1956-2007 and is arranged alphabetically by folder title. This series includes annual reports; budget reports; bylaws and constitutions and their respective amendments; executive reports; judicial reviews; handbooks; manuals; and organizational charts.

The Committee files series spans the years from 1969 to 2006 and is arranged alphabetically. This series consists of files of the committees and certain task forces within the RHA, and include minutes, policies, and general information of these committees.

The Elections files series spans the period of 1967 to 2006 and is arranged alphabetically by folder heading. This series consists of RHA election codes, election results, and files from the elections review board.

The President's Council files series, which spans from 1964 to 2006, makes up the bulk of the collection, and includes, as sub-series: Agenda and Minutes, Bills, Correspondence, Office Files, Proposals, and Resolutions. The President's Council files originally combined agenda, minutes, bills, proposals and resolutions together in one file folder per school year. Due to the differences in each of these items as research material, and to make the collection more useable, these items were separated into folders organized according to type (agenda and minutes being combined as one type), and filed as sub-series to the President's Council files. The files within these sub-series are arranged chronologically by school year, except Correspondence, which is alphabetical by author. In addition, bills that were written as amendments to the bylaws and constitution of the RHA were separated and put in folders marked "Amendments" under Bylaws or Constitution in the Administrative files.

The Subject files series spans the period 1963 to 2006 and is arranged alphabetically by folder title. Included in the series are files on the history of the RHA, policies, membership, and events in the residence halls.
The Vice President files series spans the period 2002-2005 and is arranged alphabetically. The series consists of files deal mostly with events and programs developed by the RHA.
This collection will have regular accruals.

separatedmaterial.head: Separated Material
separatedmaterial.p: A box of banners from Homecoming and other IU events, a box of 5 tshirts, as well as 3 scrapbooks and numerous photos have been removed and are stored elsewhere. Contact the Photographs Curator for further information.

userestrict.head: Usage Restrictions
userestrict.p: Copyrights for records originating with Indiana University administrative units, departments, and other offices are held by the Trustees of Indiana University. For more information, please contact the Indiana University Archives staff.

The Indiana University Archives respects the intellectual property rights of others and does not claim any copyrights for non-university records, materials in the public domain, or materials for which we do not hold a Deed of Gift. Responsibility for the determination of the copyright status of these materials rests with those persons wishing to reuse the materials. Researchers are responsible for securing permission from copyright owners and any other rights holders for any reuse of these materials that extends beyond fair use or other statutory limitations.

Digital reproductions of archival materials from the Indiana University Archives are made available for noncommercial educational and research purposes only. If you are the copyright holder for any of the digitized materials and have questions about its inclusion on our site, please contact the Indiana University Archivist.

scopecontent.head: Scope and Contents
scopecontent.p: The original file for this subject included the entire Sept. 14, 2001 issue of the Indiana Daily Student (IDS). We have photocopied a letter from the front page that was most pertinent to the RHA and discarded the newspaper.

altformavail.head: Existence and Location of Copies
altformavail.p: The full Indiana Daily Student edition for Sept. 14, 2001 can be located at the library in the Government Information, Microforms, and Statistical Services Department.

scopecontent.head: Scope and Contents
scopecontent.p: This folder contains two items that were either unidentifiable or did not fit in within the scope of the collection. One item is a set of notes written in pen with comments about an evaluation process; the first three pages of this eight-page document are missing. The second item is three pages of information on Beth Loffreda and her book Losing Matt Shepard. The first page states this item is an "Attachment", but it was not attached to any another documents in the collection
